COMMUNITY NEWS FOCUS: TUSTIN; SCHOOL OFFICIAL GIVES ADVICE ON PROP. 187 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BERT ELJERA 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 School district Supt. David Andrews has asked parents worried about passage of 
Prop. 187 to do nothing drastic and keep their children in school. 
</P>
<P>
 In a letter sent to parents earlier this week, Andrews said that it might take 
months or years before the courts resolve legal challenges to the measure, 
which was approved in the Nov. 8 election. 
</P>
<P>
 He said the California School Boards Assn. was among several groups that have 
filed suits contesting the constitutionality of the provision that would deny 
public education to children of illegal immigrants. 
</P>
<P>
 A San Francisco Superior Court judge has issued a temporary restraining order 
against the implementation of the education ban pending further hearings. 
</P>
<P>
 "I feel that Proposition 187 will be found unconstitutional in a number of 
areas, and, therefore, you must allow the courts to determine what parts are 
legal and what are not," Andrews wrote. He urged parents to call the principal 
of their children's school before making a decision. 
</P>
<P>
 "Do not do something drastic by taking your children out of school until we 
all know what the courts decide," he said. BERT ELJERA 
</P>
