<HEADLINE>
<P>
PREP EXTRA / SOUTHERN SECTION PLAYOFFS; DIVISION V; FOOTHILL'S DEFENSE SETS IN 
DEFEAT OF KENNEDY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MELANIE NEFF 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Foothill's defense dominated Friday night as the fourth-seeded Knights won 
their sixth game in a row, defeating Kennedy, 27-9, in the first round of 
Division V Southern Section playoffs at Tustin High. 
</P>
<P>
 The Knights' defense held the Fighting Irish to 141 yards of total offense and 
sacked quarterback Jason Myles four times. 
</P>
<P>
 Senior defensive linemen Rich Bowman and Tony Tuioti and sophomore linebackers 
Lawrence Mariner and Rubin Vaughn didn't give the 5-foot-7 Myles a moment's 
peace. They were in his face all night. 
</P>
<P>
 "They have been calling themselves the Black Blanket or something like that," 
Foothill Coach Tom Meiss said. "I called them the Wild Bunch all week. They 
have been uncontrollable."  
</P>
<P>
 Foothill meets Valencia, a 28-0 winner against Westminster, in the second 
round of the playoffs Friday at a site to be determined. 
</P>
<P>
 Mariner gave the Knights (7-4) their first scoring opportunity when he stepped 
in front of running back Charlie Marino and intercepted a pass by Myles. 
Mariner returned the ball 30 yards to the Irish five-yard line. Quarterback 
Tyler Lang scored on a five-yard run two plays later with six minutes and 16 
seconds remaining in the first quarter. 
</P>
<P>
 Kennedy (8-3) began the second quarter with a 60-yard drive to Foothill's 
18-yard line, but the Knights' defense was able to stall the drive and the 
Irish settled for a 36-yard field goal by Shy Azoulay. 
</P>
<P>
 On their ensuing possession with 3:45 left in the half, the Knights' Tramel 
Robinson took a swing pass at the line of scrimmage and ran around the 
defenders for a 40-yard touchdown. 
</P>
<P>
 The Knights' defense stopped Kennedy's offense in four plays. 
</P>
<P>
 Then, with six seconds remaining in the half on a fourth-and-18 play from the 
Irish 28, Lang hit sophomore Danny Monarch in the corner of the end zone to put 
the Knights up, 20-3. MELANIE NEFF 
</P>
</TEXT>
